AB  - We investigate for spillovers from monetary policy uncertainty in the United States to the policy rates of seven inflation targeting emerging economies — Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Indonesia, Mexico, Poland, and South Africa. We use monthly data, with the start of the sample period being dictated by the start of the inflation targeting regime, and a multivariate GARCH-in-Mean vector autoregression (VAR), controlling for the traditional Taylor rule type variables. We also use a multivariate structural VAR and a different measure of U.S. monetary policy uncertainty, achieving identification by a combination of short-run and long-run restrictions. Our evidence shows that U.S. monetary policy uncertainty, irrespective of how it is measured, has negative effects on the macroeconomic and financial fundamentals of emerging economies.
